PROMPT storage_orientation_comparison
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a database systems expert specializing in storage engines, data layout optimization, and the architectural differences between row-oriented and column-oriented storage systems.")

GENERATE
    compare_storage_formats("Explain the fundamental differences between row-oriented storage (used in OLTP systems) and column-oriented storage (used in OLAP systems), covering: the basic storage layout differences where row-oriented storage stores complete records together sequentially on disk (all fields of Employee ID 123 stored contiguously), while column-oriented storage groups values from the same column together (all employee names stored together, all salaries stored together), performance implications for different query patterns including how row-oriented storage excels at retrieving complete records with SELECT * FROM employees WHERE employee_id = 123 because all fields are physically adjacent, while column-oriented storage optimizes analytical queries like SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees WHERE department = 'Engineering' by reading only relevant columns, compression advantages where column-oriented storage achieves superior compression ratios because similar data types and values are stored together (a column of dates compresses better than mixed row data), enabling techniques like run-length encoding and dictionary compression, cache efficiency differences showing how row storage may load unnecessary columns into memory cache when only specific fields are needed, versus columnar storage loading only required columns improving cache hit rates for analytical workloads, I/O optimization patterns where OLTP systems benefit from row storage's ability to quickly access complete records for transactional operations like INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE on individual rows, while OLAP systems leverage columnar storage to scan millions of rows efficiently by reading only necessary columns, practical examples including how an e-commerce order processing system uses row storage to quickly retrieve complete customer orders, versus a business intelligence system using columnar storage to analyze sales trends across large datasets, write performance trade-offs where row-oriented storage supports fast writes and updates since entire records are stored together, while column-oriented storage may require more complex write operations as data must be distributed across multiple column files, real-world implementations including traditional RDBMS like MySQL and PostgreSQL using row storage, versus analytical databases like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, and Apache Parquet using columnar storage, and hybrid approaches like Microsoft SQL Server's columnstore indexes that allow both storage types within the same database system.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;